{"title_page": "Mississippi Brilla", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| nickname    = do not trust this website anyone can change anything for this \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n| capacity    = \n| season      = [[2019 USL League Two season|2019]]\n| current     = \n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = 45B1E8\n| body2       = 15406C\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = 15406C\n| shorts2     = 45B1E8\n| socks1      = 45B1E8\n\n| socks2      = 15406C\n| clubname    = Mississippi Brilla\n| image       = mississippibrilla.jpg\n| fullname    = Mississippi Brilla Futbol Club\n| founded     = {{start date and years ago|2006|||mf=yes}}\n| chrtitle    = Owner\n| chairman    = Rusty Bryant\n| mgrtitle    = Head Coach\n| manager     = Luke Sanford\n| league      = [[USL League Two]]\n| position    = 3rd, Deep South Division<br>Playoffs: DNQ\n| American    = true\n| website     = http://www.brillasoccer.org\n\n| pattern_b1  = \n| }}\n\n'''Mississippi Brilla''' is an amateur American [[association football|soccer]] club based in [[Clinton, Mississippi]], United States. Founded in 2006, the team plays in [[USL League Two]]. The team's colors are sky blue, navy and white.\n\nBrilla is associated with [[Brilla Soccer Ministries]], an organization which undertakes [[sports ministry]] to share [[Christianity]] through the sport. The club\u2019s name is derived from the [[Spanish Language|Spanish]] word for \"shine\", and references the biblical passage [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] 5:16 which says \"Therefore, let your light so shine before men that they may see your good works and glorify your Father who is in heaven.\"\n\nAlthough the club initially finished in the middle of the standings their first couple of years, Brilla has become one of the strongest PDL franchises in the [[Southeastern United States|Southeast]] on the pitch, winning their division regular season title in 2009, 2010, 2011, and 2015. In 2017, the club had their best showing in the playoffs, winning the Southern Conference Championship and advancing to the PDL Semi-finals.\n\n==History==\nMississippi Brilla entered the PDL in 2007 to a great deal of fanfare, as the first soccer franchise in [[Mississippi]] since the demise of the [[Jackson Chargers]] in 1999. Under head coach [[Dave Dixon]], Brilla tied their first game 1-1 at home to [[New Orleans Shell Shockers]] in front of over 1,000 fans (with the honor of the first goal in franchise history going to [[James Gledhill]]), and although the average attendance remained high throughout the season, the on-field results were not quite as impressive. Brilla won their first game next time out, 1-0 over [[DFW Tornados]], but then failed to register a victory in their next four games. In the end, too many ties caused Brilla's downfall - 5 on the season - and despite some impressive results, including a 5-1 hammering of [[Baton Rouge Capitals]] in June and 5-0 demolition of [[Nashville Metros]] in July, it was not quite enough to make the playoffs, and they eventually finished their freshman year fourth behind divisional (and eventual national) champions [[Laredo Heat]]. [[James Gledhill]] was the team's top scorer, with six goals, while [[Chris Rash]] and [[Tripp Harkins]] led the assists stats with three apiece.\n\nBrilla's second season in the PDL was pretty much on an equal footing with their first. With new head coach [[Steve DeCou]] at the helm, attendances remained high, often topping 900 fans per game, and the team enjoyed a number of exciting victories, including a hard-fought 2-0 win over the eventual divisional champions [[Austin Aztex U23]], a 2-1 come-from-behind victory over [[New Orleans Shell Shockers]] in mid-June, and a spectacular 6-2 final day victory at home against [[Houston Leones]] in which [[Tripp Harkins]] scored a brace. As was the case in 2007, however, Brilla's downfall was a lack of consistency, and their inability to string a series of results together to gain momentum: their longest streak was a 5-game run in late June and early which included three wins and two ties, including the aforementioned victory over New Orleans. Mississippi ended the season in 4th place in the Mid South Division, just four points out of the playoffs, and with plenty to build on in 2009. [[Phillip Buffington]] was the team's most prolific goalscorer, with 8 for the season.\n\nIn 2009 Brilla had its most successful start in team history.  Brilla qualified for the [[U.S. Open Cup]] for the first time in franchise history by going undefeated in their first four games, winning three and drawing one. [[Debola Ogunseye]] is currently the team's leading scorer with 4 goals.\n\n==Players & Staff==\n\n===Current roster===\n''As of June 2019''.<ref>https://brillasoccer.org/pages/2019-roster</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player | no=1 | nat=SPA | pos=GK | name=Alex Iglesias}}\n{{Fs player | no=2 | nat=WAL | pos=DF | name=Jacob Farthing}}\n{{Fs player | no=4 | nat=ENG | pos=DF | name=Ryan Tyrer}}\n{{Fs player | no=5 | nat=SPA | pos=DF | name=Gonzalo Talavera}}\n{{Fs player | no=6 | nat=SPA | pos=MF | name=Eduardo Zurita}}\n{{Fs player | no=7 | nat=USA | pos=DF | name=Javier Avelar}}\n{{Fs player | no=8 | nat=USA | pos=MF | name=Arturo Astorga}}\n{{Fs player | no=9 | nat=CHI | pos=FW | name=Nicolas Cam}}\n{{Fs player | no=10 | nat=JPN | pos=MF | name=Mamoru Kamisasanuki}}\n{{Fs player | no=11 | nat=TRI | pos=FW | name=Andrew Revanales}}\n{{Fs player | no=12 | nat=SPA | pos=MF | name=Abel Perez}}\n{{Fs player | no=13 | nat=USA | pos=GK | name=Nic Farr}}\n{{Fs player | no=14 | nat=FRA | pos=DF | name=Aur\u00e8le Chemin}}\n{{Fs player | no=15 | nat=USA | pos=DF | name=Jack Rittmeyer}}\n{{Fs player | no=16 | nat=USA | pos=MF | name=Duncan Storey}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player | no=17 | nat=POL | pos=FW | name=Christian Sosnowski}}\n{{Fs player | no=18 | nat=NOR | pos=FW | name=Sondre Olsen}}\n{{Fs player | no=20 | nat=USA | pos=MF | name=Nick Rieple}}\n{{Fs player | no=22 | nat=USA | pos=MF | name=Salvador Nunez}}\n{{Fs player | no=23 | nat=BRA | pos=MF | name=Victor Pimentel}}\n{{Fs player | no=25 | nat=USA | pos=GK | name=Thomas Blake}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=GHA | pos=FW | name=Isaac Boamah}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=USA | pos=MF | name=Luke Bryant}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=USA | pos=DF | name=Grant Hudson}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=ENG | pos=MF | name=Harry Reilly}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=USA | pos=MF | name=Sumner Richardson}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=NOR | pos=DF | name=Mathias Saether}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=ENG | pos=MF | name=Will Sainbury-Logan}}\n{{Fs player | no= \u2014 | nat=USA | pos=FW | name=Teren Schuster}}\n\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Head Coach===\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Luke Sanford (2019-present)\n\n===Notable Players===\n''This list of notable players comprises players who have gone on to play professional soccer after playing for the team in the Premier Development League, or those who previously played professionally before joining the team.''\n\n* {{flagicon|UGA}} [[Michael Azira]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kharlton Belmar]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kyle Clinton]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kyle Culbertson]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Devon Fisher]]\n* {{flagicon|TCA}} [[Billy Forbes (Turks and Caicos Islands footballer)|Billy Forbes]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kellen Gulley]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Chakib Hocine]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Willie Hunt]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Oscar Jimenez (soccer)|Oscar Jimenez]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Alec Kann]]\n* {{flagicon|HON}} [[Angelo Kelly-Rosales]]\n* {{flagicon|SCO}} [[David Lilly]]\n* {{flagicon|LES}} [[Napo Matsoso]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Brendan Moore]]\n* {{flagicon|NGR}} [[Debola Ogunseye]]\n* {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Lucas Paulini]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kyle Segebart]]\n* {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Jordan Skelton]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Bryce Taylor (soccer)|Bryce Taylor]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Thomas Vancaeyezeele]]\n\n===Former Head Coaches===\n* {{flagicon|Scotland}} Mark McKeever (2015-2018)\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Drew Courtney (2013-2014)\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Dave Dixon (2007, 2009\u20132012)\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Steve DeCou (2008)\n\n==Year-by-year==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Division\n!League\n!Regular Season\n!Playoffs\n!US Open Cup\n!Avg. Attendance\n|-\n|2007\n|4\n|[[2007 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|4th, Mid South\n|''Did not qualify''\n|''Did not qualify''\n|1,109 \n|-\n|2008\n|4\n|[[2008 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|4th, Mid South\n|''Did not qualify''\n|''Did not qualify''\n|935\n|-\n|2009\n|4\n|[[2009 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|bgcolor=\"B3B7FF\"|1st, Southeast\n|Divisional Finals\n|[[2009 U.S. Open Cup|1st Round]]<ref>http://thecup.us/2009/06/09/austin-aztex-usl-1-20-mississippi-brilla-pdl/</ref>\n|852\n|-\n|2010\n|4\n|[[2010 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|bgcolor=\"B3B7FF\"|1st, Southeast\n|Conference Semifinals\n|''Did not qualify''\n|671\n|-\n|2011\n|4\n|[[2011 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|bgcolor=\"B3B7FF\"|1st, Southeast\n|Conference Finals\n|''Did not qualify''\n|732\n|-\n|2012\n|4\n|[[2012 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|4th, Southeast\n|''Did not qualify''\n|[[2012 U.S. Open Cup|1st Round]]<ref>http://thecup.us/2012/05/16/2012-us-open-cup-first-round-georgia-revolution-edge-mississippi-brilla-1-0-in-ot</ref>\n|502\n|-\n|2013\n|4\n|[[2013 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|5th, Southeast\n|''Did not qualify''\n|''Did not qualify''\n|564\n|-\n|2014\n|4\n|[[2014 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|4th, Mid South\n|''Did not qualify''\n|''Did not qualify''\n|597\n|-\n|2015\n|4\n|[[2015 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|bgcolor=\"B3B7FF\"|1st, Mid South\n|Conference Semifinals\n|''Did not qualify''\n|709\n|-\n|2016\n|4\n|[[2016 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|3rd, Mid South\n|''Did not qualify''\n|[[2016 U.S. Open Cup|2nd Round]]<ref>https://www.ussoccer.com/lamar-hunt-us-open-cup/open-cup-tournaments/2016-usoc/second-round/160518-usoc-second-round-okc-energy-fc-at-mississippi-brilla-fc</ref>\n|\u2014\n|-\n|2017\n|4\n|[[2017 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|2nd, Mid South\n|National Semifinals\n|''Did not qualify''\n|\u2014\n|-\n|2018\n|4\n|[[2018 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|2nd, Deep South\n|''Did not qualify''\n|[[2018 U.S. Open Cup|3rd Round]]<ref>https://www.ussoccer.com/lamar-hunt-us-open-cup/open-cup-tournaments/2018-usoc/2018-us-open-cup-third-round/20180523-us-open-cup-third-round-nashville-sc-vs-mississippi-brilla-fc</ref>\n|\u2014\n|-\n|2019\n|4\n|[[2019 USL League Two season|USL League Two]]\n|3rd, Deep South\n|''Did not qualify''\n|''Did not qualify''\n|\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honors==\n* USL PDL Southeast Division Champions 2009\n* USL PDL Southeast Division Champions 2010\n* USL PDL Southeast Division Champions 2011\n* USL PDL Mid South Division Champions 2015\n* USL PDL Southern Conference Champions 2017\n\n==Stadium==\n* Robert P. Longabaugh Field; [[Mississippi College]]; [[Clinton, Mississippi]] (2007-2009)\n* Harper Davis Stadium; [[Millsaps College]]; [[Jackson, Mississippi]] (2007, 2010\u20132012)\n* M&F Bank Stadium (Freedom Ridge Park); [[Ridgeland, Mississippi]] (2 games in 2008-2009)\n* Traceway Park, [[Clinton, Mississippi]] (4 games in 2015, 2016)\n* Arrow Field at [[Clinton High School (Clinton, Mississippi)|Clinton High School]]; [[Clinton, Mississippi]] (3 games in 2008-2010, 2013\u20132015, 2017-present)\n\n==Supporters==\nThe Mississippi Brilla supporter club is The Blue Battalion,<ref>https://www.facebook.com/BlueBattalion516</ref> founded in 2015.  The Battalion tailgate before each home game and bring passion and noise to match days. Each home game the group selects their player of the game, who signs the large Blue Battalion flag.\n\n==Broadcasts==\nEach Mississippi Brilla home game is broadcast live on their [[YouTube]] channel and also kept there for on demand viewing.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCiVYC2Gy675-vO_vMguUFMg</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brillasoccer.org Official Site]\n*[https://www.uslleaguetwo.com/page/show/4731473-mississippi-brilla-fc Official PDL site]\n\n{{USL League Two}}\n{{Mississippi Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2006]]\n[[Category:USL League Two teams]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Hinds County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| nickname    = Brilla\n| stadium      = Clinton Arrow Stadium<BR>[[Clinton, Mississippi]]\n| capacity    = \n| season      = [[2019 USL League Two season|2019]]\n| current     = \n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = 45B1E8\n| body2       = 15406C\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = 15406C\n| shorts2     = 45B1E8\n| socks1      = 45B1E8\n\n| socks2      = 15406C\n| clubname    = Mississippi Brilla\n| image       = mississippibrilla.jpg\n| fullname    = Mississippi Brilla Futbol Club\n| founded     = {{start date and years ago|2006|||mf=yes}}\n| chrtitle    = Owner\n| chairman    = Rusty Bryant\n| mgrtitle    = Head Coach\n| manager     = Luke Sanford\n| league      = [[USL League Two]]\n| position    = 3rd, Deep South Division<br>Playoffs: DNQ\n| American    = true\n| website     = http://www.brillasoccer.org\n\n| pattern_b1  = \n| }}\n\n'''Mississippi Brilla''' is an amateur American [[association football|soccer]] club based in [[Clinton, Mississippi]], United States. Founded in 2006, the team plays in [[USL League Two]]. The team's colors are sky blue, navy and white.\n\nBrilla is associated with [[Brilla Soccer Ministries]], an organization which undertakes [[sports ministry]] to share [[Christianity]] through the sport. The club\u2019s name is derived from the [[Spanish Language|Spanish]] word for \"shine\", and references the biblical passage [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] 5:16 which says \"Therefore, let your light so shine before men that they may see your good works and glorify your Father who is in heaven.\"\n\nAlthough the club initially finished in the middle of the standings their first couple of years, Brilla has become one of the strongest PDL franchises in the [[Southeastern United States|Southeast]] on the pitch, winning their division regular season title in 2009, 2010, 2011, and 2015. In 2017, the club had their best showing in the playoffs, winning the Southern Conference Championship and advancing to the PDL Semi-finals.\n\n==History==\nMississippi Brilla entered the PDL in 2007 to a great deal of fanfare, as the first soccer franchise in [[Mississippi]] since the demise of the [[Jackson Chargers]] in 1999. Under head coach [[Dave Dixon]], Brilla tied their first game 1-1 at home to [[New Orleans Shell Shockers]] in front of over 1,000 fans (with the honor of the first goal in franchise history going to [[James Gledhill]]), and although the average attendance remained high throughout the season, the on-field results were not quite as impressive. Brilla won their first game next time out, 1-0 over [[DFW Tornados]], but then failed to register a victory in their next four games. In the end, too many ties caused Brilla's downfall - 5 on the season - and despite some impressive results, including a 5-1 hammering of [[Baton Rouge Capitals]] in June and 5-0 demolition of [[Nashville Metros]] in July, it was not quite enough to make the playoffs, and they eventually finished their freshman year fourth behind divisional (and eventual national) champions [[Laredo Heat]]. [[James Gledhill]] was the team's top scorer, with six goals, while [[Chris Rash]] and [[Tripp Harkins]] led the assists stats with three apiece.\n\nBrilla's second season in the PDL was pretty much on an equal footing with their first. With new head coach [[Steve DeCou]] at the helm, attendances remained high, often topping 900 fans per game, and the team enjoyed a number of exciting victories, including a hard-fought 2-0 win over the eventual divisional champions [[Austin Aztex U23]], a 2-1 come-from-behind victory over [[New Orleans Shell Shockers]] in mid-June, and a spectacular 6-2 final day victory at home against [[Houston Leones]] in which [[Tripp Harkins]] scored a brace. As was the case in 2007, however, Brilla's downfall was a lack of consistency, and their inability to string a series of results together to gain momentum: their longest streak was a 5-game run in late June and early which included three wins and two ties, including the aforementioned victory over New Orleans. Mississippi ended the season in 4th place in the Mid South Division, just four points out of the playoffs, and with plenty to build on in 2009. [[Phillip Buffington]] was the team's most prolific goalscorer, with 8 for the season.\n\nIn 2009 Brilla had its most successful start in team history.  Brilla qualified for the [[U.S. Open Cup]] for the first time in franchise history by going undefeated in their first four games, winning three and drawing one. [[Debola Ogunseye]] is currently the team's leading scorer with 4 goals.\n\n==Players & Staff==\n\n===Current roster===\n''As of June 2019''.<ref>https://brillasoccer.org/pages/2019-roster</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player | no=1 | nat=SPA | pos=GK | name=Alex Iglesias}}\n{{Fs player | no=2 | nat=WAL | pos=DF | name=Jacob Farthing}}\n{{Fs player | no=4 | nat=ENG | pos=DF | name=Ryan Tyrer}}\n{{Fs player | no=5 | nat=SPA | pos=DF | name=Gonzalo Talavera}}\n{{Fs player | no=6 | nat=SPA | pos=MF | name=Eduardo Zurita}}\n{{Fs player | no=7 | nat=USA | pos=DF | name=Javier Avelar}}\n{{Fs player | no=8 | nat=USA | pos=MF | name=Arturo Astorga}}\n{{Fs player | no=9 | nat=CHI | pos=FW | name=Nicolas Cam}}\n{{Fs player | no=10 | nat=JPN | pos=MF | name=Mamoru Kamisasanuki}}\n{{Fs player | no=11 | nat=TRI | pos=FW | name=Andrew Revanales}}\n{{Fs player | no=12 | nat=SPA | pos=MF | nam