623f\u65b0\u793e--> |year=1996 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CvxsAAAAIAAJ |page=}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sakka-onsite.jp/sasazawasaho/ Saho Sasazawa Official Homepage]\n* [http://www.mikazukimura.com/kinenkan.php Kogarashi Monjir\u014d Memorial Museum]\n* [https://www2.nhk.or.jp/archives/jinbutsu/detail.cgi?das_id=D0016010250_00000 Saho Sasazawa] via {{illm|NHK Archives Portal{{!}}NHK jinbutsuroku|ja|NHK\u30a2\u30fc\u30ab\u30a4\u30d6\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30bf\u30eb}}<!--NHK\u4eba\u7269\u9332: no redirect; this link is in the {{template:NHK\u4eba\u7269\u9332}}--> (brief biographical video on NHK TV)\n{{-}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sasazawa, Saho}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n<!--[[Category:\u7b39\u6ca2\u5de6\u4fdd|*]]-->\n[[Category:Japanese mystery writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese novelists]]\n[[Category:Mystery Writers of Japan Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo Metropolis]]\n[[Category:People from Yokohama]]\n[[Category:Kanto Gakuin University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Saho Sasazawa\n| pseudonym     = Saho Sasazawa<!--\u7b39\u6ca2 \u4f50\u4fdd-->\n| birth_name    = Masaru Sasazawa \n| birth_date    = November 15, 1930\n| birth_place   = [[Tokyo Prefecture]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2002|10|21|1930|11|15}}\n| death_place   = [[Komae, Tokyo]]\n| occupation    = novelist\n| nationality   = {{JPN}}\n| period        = \n| genre         = {{illm|Period novel|ja|\u6642\u4ee3\u5c0f\u8aac}}, [[Detective fiction|mystery]], Suspense\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks = ''[[Kogarashi Monjir\u014d]]''\n| awards        = \n| <!--debut_works   = ''Manekarezaru kyaku''--><!--\u300e\u62db\u304b\u308c\u3056\u308b\u5ba2\u300f-->\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Sasazawa Saho'''|\u7b39\u6ca2\u5de6\u4fdd||extra=<!--Use the MOS-JA guideline for the real name \u2013 Put his real name in Western order-->November 15, 1930 \u2013 October 21, 2002}} was a [[Japanese author]], known as the creator of the ''[[Kogarashi Monjir\u014d]]'' novels, which became a hit televised drama series.\n\nHe was a self-declared member of the {{illm|honkaku-ha{{!}}''shinhonkaku-ha''|ja|\u672c\u683c\u6d3e\u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aac}} or \"new orthodox\" school of detective fiction writing. Aside from [[detective fiction|mysteries]], he also wrote [[Thriller (genre)|thrillers]], essays and history books, with some 380 books to his credit.\n\n== Life and works ==\nSaho Sasazwa was born {{nihongo|'''Masaru Sasazawa'''|\u7b39\u6ca2\u52dd}}, the third son of poet {{illm|Yoshiaki Sasazawa|ja|\u7b39\u6ca2\u7f8e\u660e}}.<ref name=gendai-sakka-jiten/> Born in [[Yokohama]] according to many sources,<ref name=gendai-sakka-jiten/> but it has also been said he was actually born in [[Yodobashi, Tokyo]] and later moved to Yokohama.<ref name=bungeishunju/> There he attended what is now [[Kanto Gakuin University]]'s high school division, but failed to graduate,<ref name=yomiuri-jinmeiroku/> frequently running away from home during this period.<ref name=bungeishunju/>\n\nBy 1952 he was in Tokyo, working at the {{illm|Postal Insurance|ja|\u7c21\u6613\u4fdd\u967a}} Bureau run by the [[Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications (Japan)|Postal Ministry]].<ref name=bungeishunju/><ref name=herbert/> Around this time he dabbled in writing plays.<ref name=penname-jiten/>\n\nIn 1958, he was struck by a [[DUI]] car, suffering injuries expecting to take 8 months to fully heal.<ref name=bungeishunju/><ref name=herbert/> But his short stories {{nihongo|''Yami no naka no dengon''|\u95c7\u306e\u4e2d\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00|extra=\"The message in the dark\"}} and {{nihongo|''Kunin me no giseisha''|\u4e5d\u4eba\u76ee\u306e\u72a0\u7272\u8005|extra=\"The ninth victim\"}}, which he had submitted to prize contest before the accident both qualified and were printed in the December 1958 special issue of the ''Hoseki'' magazine.<ref name=seiki/><ref name=herbert/>\n\nIn 1960,{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|In 1960, after his work ''Kunsh\u014d'' (\"Medal\") was also selected among notables in the short fiction contest co-run by ''Shukan Asahi'' and ''Hoseki''.<ref name=seiki/>}} his {{nihongo|''Manekarezaru kyaku''|\u62db\u304b\u308c\u3056\u308b\u5ba2|extra=\"The uninvited guest\"}} became a runner-up for the 5th [[Edogawa Rampo Prize]],<ref name=seiki/><ref name=kokubungaku-ozaki/> and the release of this in book format marked his debut as novelist.<ref name=bungeishunju/><ref name=penname-jiten/><ref name=herbert/>\n\nHe adopted the [[pen name]] Saho, which was taken from his wife's name {{nihongo|Sahoko|\u4f50\u4fdd\u5b50}}.<ref name=bungeishunju/>{{efn|His name was originally styled {{nihongo|Saho|\u4f50\u4fdd}} but was changed to {{nihongo|Saho|\u5de6\u4fdd}} using a different character, in 1961.<ref name=gendai-sakka-jiten/>}}\n\nHis {{nihongo|''Hitokui''|\u4eba\u55b0\u3044|extra=\"Man-eater\", 1961}} was awarded the 14th [[Mystery Writers of Japan Award]], after which he resigned from the Postal Ministry and became a full-time professional writer.<ref name=kokubungaku-ozaki/><ref name=bungeishunju/>\n\nWith his {{nihongo|''Roppongi shinj\u016b''|\u516d\u672c\u6728\u5fc3\u4e2d|extra=\"Roppongi double-suicide\"}} (1962) he received his third nomination for the prestigious semi-annual [[Naoki Prize]] for popular fiction.<ref name=domeki/> He had been twice nominated for the prize before, for ''Hitokui'' and {{nihongo|''K\u016bhaku no kiten''|\u7a7a\u767d\u306e\u8d77\u70b9|extra=\"Starting point of blankness\"}},{{sfnp|Shinpo|1996|p=40}} and although he was short-listed to win this time,{{efn|An \"editor from the publisher sponsoring the [prize, i.e. Bungeishunju-sha] flatly declared [Sasazawa] is unmistakeably going to win<!--\u4e3b\u50ac\u306e\u51fa\u7248\u793e\u306e\u7de8\u96c6\u8005\u306f\u76f4\u6728\u8cde\u307e\u3061\u304c\u3044\u306a\u3057\u3001\u3068\u65ad\u8a00\u3057\u3066\u3044\u305f-->\", according to Akira Miki, a former editor for Kodansha.}}<ref name=miki/> he was disappointed once again.<ref name=kokubungaku-endo-tasuku/>{{efn|[[Seich\u014d Matsumoto]] and {{illm|Keita Genji|ja|\u6e90\u6c0f\u9d8f\u592a}} pushed for Sasazawa's ''Roppongi shinj\u016b'' but other panelists disagreed, and the award was shared by two other authors, [[Hitomi Yamaguchi]] for {{illm|Eburi man shi no y\u016bga na seikatsu{{!}}''Eburi man shi no y\u016bga na seikatsu''|ja|\u6c5f\u5206\u5229\u6e80\u6c0f\u306e\u512a\u96c5\u306a\u751f\u6d3b}} and [[Sonoko Sugimoto]] for ''Kosh\u016b no kishi''<!--\u300e\u5b64\u6101\u306e\u5cb8\u300f-->.}} Around this time, while declaring himself to be one of the practitioners of ''[[Japanese detective fiction#development|honkaku-ha]]'' ([[:ja:\u672c\u683c\u6d3e\u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aac|\u672c\u683c\u6d3e]]) or \"orthodox school\" of mystery fiction-writing,{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|Kenkyusha's ''Shin wa-ei ch\u016b-jiten'' dictionary (4th ed., 1995) has a subentry on ''honkaku-ha\" and gives the translation \"orthodox school\". On ''honkaku-teki'' it gives three senses: \"genuine, real\", \"orthodox\", or \"standard\".\nAmanda C. Seaman says: \"..what Japanese critics call &lsquo;''honkaku-ha''&rsquo;, or standard, detective fiction.}} he wrote a trilogy on double-suicide without homicide;<ref name=gendai-sakka-jiten/> of these, the Naoki Prize-nominated ''Roppongi Double-Suicide'' was appraised as a piece \"depicting empty love between a young man and a girl\", which entwined \"the drama of loss of faith in humanity\" into the mystery novel.<ref name=domeki/>\n\nIn 1970, he ventured into writing {{illm|period novel{{!}}period novels|ja|\u6642\u4ee3\u5c0f\u8aac}} (in particular ''matatabi'' fiction about traveling gamblers) with {{nihongo|''Mikaeri t\u014dge no rakujitsu''|\u898b\u8fd4\u308a\u5ce0\u306e\u843d\u65e5|extra=\"Sunset at Look-back Pass\"}}.<ref name=gendai-sakka-jiten/> Sasazawa's style of this gambler fiction has been characterized as \"casting a nihilistic shadow, an added an aura of Cowboy Westerns\".<!--\u30cb\u30d2\u30eb\u306e\u5f71\u3092\u843d\u3068\u3057\u897f\u90e8\u5287\u30bf\u30c3\u30c1\u3092\u52a0\u3048\u305f--><ref name=gendai-sakka-jiten/> The samurai period gambler piece that brought Sasazawa lasting fame was his [[Kogarashi Monjir\u014d]] series,<ref name=gendai-sakka-jiten/><ref name=herbert/> begun with the episode entitled {{nihongo|''Shamen bana wa chitta''|\u8d66\u514d\u82b1\u306f\u6563\u3063\u305f|extra=\"The Clemency Flower has Scattered\", 1970}}. The book was TV-dramatized with [[Atsuo Nakamura]] playing the leading role of the gambler Monjir\u014d, and the program achieved immense popularity.<ref name=herbert/><ref name=bungeishunju/><ref>{{harvnb|Shinpo|1996|p=34}}.<!--\u662d\u548c\u56db\u5341\u516d\u5e74\u4ee5\u964d\u3001\u6728\u67af\u3057\n\u7d0b\u6b21\u90ce\u306e\u5275\u9020\u306b\u3088\u3063\u3066\u80a1\u65c5\u7269\u306e\u9f8d\u5150\u3068\u306a\u3063\u305f\u6642\u3082\u3001\u5e74\u9593\u306b\u6700\u4f4e\u4e00\u518a\u306f\u63a8\u7406\u9577\u7bc7\u306e\u520a\u884c\"--></ref><ref name=tv-gensaku-databook/>\n\nHe continued to write fiction in both contemporary and period settings.\n\nSome of his outputs in modern settings from the subsequent period include the child-kidnapping novel {{nihongo|''Mayonaka no shijin''|\u771f\u591c\u4e2d\u306e\u8a69\u4eba|extra=\"Midnight poet\", 1972}}, called a masterpiece on par with his earlier great works;<ref>{{harvnb|Shinpo|1996|p=40}}.<!--\"\u7d0b\u6b21\u90ce \"\u3053\u306e\u9593.. \u63a8\u7406\u9577\u7de8\u3067\u521d\u671f\u5091\u4f5c\u306b\u5339\u6575\u3059\u308b\u4f5c\u54c1\u3068\u3057\u3066\u306f\u3001\u300e\u771f\u591c\u4e2d\u306e\u8a69\u4eba\u300f,\u300e\u4e09\u4eba\u306e\u767b\u5834\u4eba\u7269\u300f--></ref> {{nihongo|''Haruka nari waga ai o''|\u9065\u304b\u306a\u308a\u308f\u304c\u611b\u3092|extra=\"My love so far\", 1976}} which launched the Detective Isenami series;{{sfnp|Shinpo|1996|p=42}}<!--\u4f0a\u52e2\u6ce2\u90a6\u5f66\u306f\u65e5\u672c\u53f2\u3092\u5c02\u653b\u3057\u305f\u5909\u308a\u7a2e\u306e\u8b66\u90e8\u3067..\u6b74\u53f2\u63a8\u7406\u3068\u30a2\u30ea\u30d1\u30a4\u304f\u305a\u3057\u3092\u30ab\u30af\u30c6\u30eb\u306b\u3057\u305f\u7570\u8272\u306e\u9023\u4f5c\u3067\u6d3b\u8e8d\u3059\u308b-->{{nihongo|''Tasatsu misaki''|\u4ed6\u6bba\u5cac|extra=\"Cape homicide\", 1977}} was a time-limit kidnapping story with a twist,<ref name=bungei-nenkan1977/> the scandal-monger must devise a ransom for the perpetrator who only wants vengeance; {{nihongo|''Ky\u016bkon no misshitsu''|\u6c42\u5a5a\u306e\u5bc6\u5ba4|extra=\"The marriage-proposing locked room\", 1978}} features a well-crafted [[locked room mystery|locked room]] gimmickry.<ref>{{harvp|Shinpo|1996|pp=32, 42}}</ref>\n\nHe has also became well known at one time for ''Akuma no heya'' (\"Devil's room\", 1981) and its sequels in his ''Akuma'' (\"Devil\") series of erotic suspense-thriller novels ({{nihongo||\u5b98\u80fd\u30b5\u30b9\u30da\u30f3\u30b9|''kann\u014d sasupensu''}},<ref name=ouchi/> this being a hybrid genre between the {{illm|erotic novel|ja|\u5b98\u80fd\u5c0f\u8aac}} and suspense-thriller.\n\nHis {{nihongo|''Aribai no uta''|\u30a2\u30ea\u30d0\u30a4\u306e\u5504|extra=\"Alibi song\", 1990}} started the Hideo Yoake casefile series of novels, dramatized on TV as the {{illm|Taxi Driver's Mystery Diary{{!}}''Taxi Driver's Mystery Diary''|ja|\u30bf\u30af\u30b7\u30fc\u30c9\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30fc\u306e\u63a8\u7406\u65e5\u8a8c}} starring [[Tsunehiko Watase]];<ref>{{harvp|Et\u014d|2005|p=150}}</ref> The TV series {{illm|Torishirabe shitsu{{!}}''Torishirabe shitsu''|ja|\u53d6\u8abf\u5ba4 (\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u30c9\u30e9\u30de)}} \"Interrogation room\" ran its first episode in 1994 based on the novel of the same title published 1993.<ref name=tv-gensaku-databook/>\n\nPeriod pieces in other than his ''Monjir\u014d'' include {{nihongo|''Sasurai kaid\u014d''|\u3055\u3059\u3089\u3044\u8857\u9053|extra=\"Wandering highway\", 1972}} which employs mystery novel techniques in historical settings,<ref name=kobunsha-sasurai-kaido/> the Jigoku no Tatsu crime-solving novels (1972\u2013), televised as {{nihongo|''Jigoku no Tatsu torimono hikae''|[[:ja:\u5730\u7344\u306e\u8fb0\u6355\u7269\u63a7|\u5730\u7344\u306e\u8fb0\u6355\u7269\u63a7]]|extra2=\"Tatsu from hell's Casebook\"}};<ref name=\"harvp|Et\u014d|2005|p=148\">{{harvp|Et\u014d|2005|p=148}}</ref> another TV-dramtized series on {{illm|Hanmi no Okon|ja|\u5973\u7121\u5bbf\u4eba \u534a\u8eab\u306e\u304a\u7d3a}} (1974\u2013),<ref name=\"harvp|Et\u014d|2005|p=148\"/> whose title character Okon bears a tattoo which forms a complete dragon when combined with her lover's.\n\nDuring his lifetime he published some 377 books.<ref name=bungeishunju/><ref name=bunshun-books/><ref name=jomo-shimbun2002-10-22/>\n\nWith declining health in 1987, he recuperated at a hospital in the town of [[Mikatsuki, Saga]] which bore a name similar to {{illm|Mikazuki-mura|ja|\u4e09\u65e5\u6708\u6751}} (Mikazuki Village), the fictitious birthplace of Monjir\u014d. After being discharged, he made the adjacent town of [[Fuji, Saga|Fujich\u014d]] his home,<ref name=nishinihon-shinbun/> and although he had to relocate in 1995 to {{illm|Hyogo, Saga{{!}}Hyogomachi|ja|\u5175\u5eab (\u4f50\u8cc0\u5e02)}} in [[Saga (city)|Saga]] city for hospital access, the Fujich\u014d residence later became the Sasazawa Saho Memorial Museum.<ref name=nishinihon-shinbun/>\n\nHe established the {{illm|Kyushu Saga Taish\u016bbungaku Prize|ja|\u4e5d\u5dde\u3055\u304c\u5927\u8846\u6587\u5b66\u8cde}} for literature by new authors in 1993, with the final 24th prize awarded in 2017.<ref name=nishinihon-shinbun/><ref name=mainichi2017-03-28/>\n\nIn 2001 he returned to [[Kodaira, Tokyo]],<ref name=nishinihon-shinbun/> and succumbed to liver cancer ([[Hepatocellular carcinoma|HCC]]) on 21 October 2002 at a hospital in [[Komae, Tokyo]].<ref name=jomo-shimbun2002-10-22/>\n\n=== Legacy and influence ===\nHe was a prolific writer, who at his height wrote 1,000 or even 1,500 pages of manuscript per month,<ref name=saga-shimbun2019-10-10/><ref>{{harvp|Menj\u014d|2013}} apud [https://blogos.com/article/107481/ BLOGOS], review, 2015-03-10.</ref>\u3001he has been called a \"constant innovator\" <ref name=domeki/><!--\"\u3064\u306d\u306b\u65b0\u3057\u3044\u65b0\u6a5f\u8ef8\u3092\u751f\u307f\u51fa\u3057\"--> or experimenter. In particular, Sasazawa is known for applying the mystery novel techniques of \"surprise-twist endings (''donden-gaeshi'')\" and climatic endings in writing ''matatabi'' fiction, thus introducing a fresh angle in the fiction about these wandering rogue swordsman-gamblers.<ref name=kaisetsu/><!--\"\u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aac\u306e\u624b\u6cd5(\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u3069\u3093\u3067\u3093\u304c\u3048\u3057\u306e\u9bae\u3084\u304b\u3055\u7b49)\u3092\u3053\u306e\u80a1\u65c5\u7269\u306b\u3082\u5fdc\u7528\u3057\u3001\u5f93\u6765\u306e\u6642\u4ee3\u5c0f\u8aac\u306b\u306f\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f\u7269\u8a9e\u69cb\u6210\u306e\u5999\u5473\u3092\u793a\u3057\u305f\u3053\u3068\u3082\u3042\u3063\u3066\u3001\u7b39\u6ca2\u80a1\u65c5\u5c0f\u8aac..\"--><ref name=kokubungaku-musashino/><!--\"\u65b0\u30fb\u80a1\u65c5\u5c0f\u8aac\u306e\u7279\u5fb4\u3067\u3044\u3061\u3070\u3093\u306b\u6ce8\u76ee\u3055\u308c\u305f\u306e\u306f\u3001\u305d\u306e\u66f8\u304d\u624b\u3068\u3057\u3066\u3001\u63a8\u7406\u4f5c\u5bb6\u306e\u9762\u3005\u304c\u8d77\u7528\u3055\u308c\u305f\u3053\u3068\u3067\u3042\u308b\u3002...\u305f\u3068\u3048\u3070\u3001\u3069\u3093\u3067\u3093\u8fd4\u3057\u306e\u624b\u6cd5...\u306a\u304b\u3067\u3082\u3001\u3059\u3067\u306b\u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aac\u754c\u3067\u306f\u4eba\u6c17\u4f5c\u5bb6\u3068\u3057\u3066\u6d3b\u8e8d\u3057\u3066\u3044\u305f\u7b39\u6ca2\u5de6\u4fdd\u304c\u57f7\u7b46\u767a\u8868\u3057\u305f\u80a1\u65c5\u77ed\u7bc7\u300c\u898b\u304b\u3048\u308a\u5ce0\u300d\"-->\n\nHe wrote a study in sensual-erotic suspense with the novel {{nihongo|''Akuma no heya''|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u90e8\u5c4b|extra=\"Demon's Room\"}}<ref name=ouchi/> which was adapted into film, and crime novels consisting entirely of conversation, such as {{nihongo|''Donden gaeshi''|\u3069\u3093\u3067\u3093\u8fd4\u3057|extra=\"the flip-reversal\"}},<ref name=naito/> and {{nihongo|''D\u014dgy\u014dsha''|\u540c\u884c\u8005|extra=\"fellow believer of the path\"}},{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|Originally tilted ''Akuma no michizure''. The although the title can be read ''d\u014dk\u014dsha'', the ''d\u014dgy\u014dsha'' reading is confirmed,<ref>[https://ndlonline.ndl.go.jp/#!/detail/R300000001-I000001660689-00 ''D\u014dgy\u014dsha''] via NDL-online.</ref> as well as its meaning.<ref>\"[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%90%8C%E8%A1%8C-103312 d\u014dgy\u014dsha''|\u540c\u884c]\" via kotobank.</ref>}}<ref name=kobunsha-akuma-no-michizure/> and {{nihongo|''Ushiro sugata no seiz\u014d''|\u5f8c\u308d\u59ff\u306e\u8056\u50cf|extra=\"rear-view icon\"}} where the alibi trick undergoes a complete 180-degrees plot-twist.{{efn|Later retitled ''Moshimo omae ga furimuita nara'' (\"If Ever You Look Behind You\")}}<ref>{{harvp|Shinpo|1996|p=42}}<!--quote:\"\u5f97\u610f\u306e\u30a2\u30ea\u30d0\u30a4\u30fb\u30c6\u30fc\u30de\u3092\u88cf\u8fd4\u3057\u305f\u300e\u5f8c\u308d\u59ff\u306e\u8056\u50cf\u300f(\u662d\u548c\u4e94\u5341\u516d\u5e74\u3001\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u3001\u65b0\u66f8\u5316\u4ee5\u964d\u300e\u3082\u3057\u3082\u304a\u524d\u304c\u632f\u308a\u5411\u3044\u305f\u3089\u300f\u3068\u6539\u984c)\"\u3002--></ref>\n\nHe held a staunch purist stance about detective fiction writing. Sasazawa identified himself as a proponent of the {{nihongo|''Shin-honkaku-ha''|\u65b0\u672c\u683c\u6d3e|extra2=\"New Orthodox School\" or \"New Authentic School\"}}. Such a writer, he explained, was not only required to be \"orthodox\" (or \"authentic\") and devise a clever trick used in the crime, but in addition, needed to maintain realisticness in the human characters employed.<ref name=kokubungaku-ozaki/><ref name=bungeishunju/><ref>{{harvp|Shinpo|1996|p=34}}<!--\"\u7d14\u7136\u305f\u308b\u672c\u683c\u63a8\u7406\u300e\u62db\u304b\u308c\u3056\u308b\u5ba2\u300f\u3067\u51fa\u767a\u3057\u305f\u7b39\u6ca2\u5de6\u4fdd\u306e\u6301\u8ad6\u306f\u3001\u672c\u683c\u7269\u306f\u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aac\u306e\u57fa\u790e\u3068\u3044\u3046\u3053\u3068\u3067\u3042\u3063\u305f\u3002\u3060\u304c\u3001\u3053\u308c\u304b\u3089\u306e\u672c\u683c\u7269\u306f\u8b0e\u3068\u304d\u3070\u304b\u308a\u3067\u306a\u304f\u3001\u30ed\u30de\u30f3\u3068\u793e\u4f1a\u6027\u3068\u30ea\u30a2\u30ea\u30c6\u30a3\u3092\u3082\u91cd\u8996\u3057\u305f\u65b0\u672c\u683c\u3067\u306a\u3051\u308c\u3070\u306a\u3089\u306a\u3044\u3068\u8aac\"\u3044\u305f\u3002--></ref><ref name=kokubungaku-ozaki2/><!--\"\u305d\u306e\u9803\u304b\u3089\u672c\u683c\u6d3e\u3068\u3044\u3046\u30ec\u30c3\u30c6\u30eb\u3092\u306f\u3089\u308c\u305f\u306e\u3067\u3001\u3053\u3053\u3067\u65b0\u672c\u683c\u6d3e\u3068\u3044\u3046\u306e\u3092\u8a66\u307f\u308b\u6b32\u671b\u3092\u3060\u3057\u305f\u307e\u3067\u3067\u3059\u300d\u3068\u8a9e\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\"... \"\u7b39\u6ca2\u5de6\u4fdd\u306e\u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aac\u306f\u672c\u683c\u3082\u306e\u3067\u306f\u3058\u307e\u308a\u3001\u3084\u304c\u3066\u4eba\u7269\u8a2d\u5b9a\u306b\u30ea\u30a2\u30ea\u30c6\u30a3\u3092\u304a\u3044\u305f\u4f5c\u98a8\u306b\u79fb\u884c\u3057\u3001\u307f\u305a\u304b\u3089\u65b0\u672c\u683c\u6d3e\u3068\u79f0\u3059... \" --> When he sat on the selection panel for the [[Edogawa Rampo Prize]], he repeatedly bewailed the laxening of the definition of what could be considered \"detective fiction\".{{sfnp|Sekiguchi|2000|p=302}} In 1977, he wrote an essay that polemicized against the [[novel of manners]] contaminating the mystery fiction genre.<ref>\"F\u016bzoku sh\u014dsetsuka no k\u014dzai \u98a8\u4fd7\u5c0f\u8aac\u5316\u306e\u529f\u7f6a\" ''Suiri sh\u014dsetsu kenky\u016b'' \u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aac\u7814\u7a76, (7).</ref>{{sfnp|Sekiguchi|2000|p=186}}{{sfnp|Shinpo|1996|p=40}}\n\n== Selected works ==\n=== Modern mysteries ===\n====The ''Misaki'' (\"Cape\") series====\n*{{nihongo|''Tasatsu misaki''|\u4ed6\u6bba\u5cac|extra=\"Cape Homicide\"}}, 1976\n*{{nihongo|''Furin misaki''|\u4e0d\u502b\u5cac|extra=\"Cape Adultery\"}}, 1978\n*{{nihongo|''Muj\u014d misaki''|\u7121\u60c5\u5cac|extra=\"Cape Merciless\"}}, 1979\n*{{nihongo|''T\u014db\u014d misaki''|\u9003\u4ea1\u5cac|extra=\"Cape Escape\"}}, 1981\n*{{nihongo|''Aijin misaki''|\u611b\u4eba\u5cac|extra=\"Cape Lover\"}}, 1981\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma misaki''|\u60aa\u9b54\u5cac|extra=\"Cape Devil\"}}, 1985\n*{{nihongo|''Zansh\u014d misaki''|\u6b8b\u7167\u5cac|extra=\"Cape Afterglow\"}}, 1987\n\n====The ''Akuma'' (\"Devil\") series====\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma no heya''|[[:ja:\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u90e8\u5c4b|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u90e8\u5c4b]]|extra=\"The Devil's Chamber\"}}, 1981\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma no kohan''|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u6e56\u7554|extra=\"The Devil's Lakeside\"}}, 1981\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma no kankei''|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u95a2\u4fc2|extra=\"The Devil's Relationship\"}}, 1982\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma no hitojichi''|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u4eba\u8cea|extra=\"The Devil's Hostage\"}}, 1982\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma no chinmoku''|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u6c88\u9ed9|extra=\"The Devil's Silence\"}}, 1983\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma no y\u016bwaku''|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u8a98\u60d1|extra=\"The Devil's Enticement\"}}, 1983\n*{{nihongo|''Akuma no shokei''|\u60aa\u9b54\u306e\u51e6\u5211|extra=\"The Devil's Execution\"}}, 1994\n\n====The ''Y\u014dbi'' (\"Days of the Week\") series====\n*{{nihongo|''Onna wa getsuy\u014dbi ni naku''|\u5973\u306f\u6708\u66dc\u65e5\u306b\u6ce3\u304f|extra=\"The Woman Weeps on Monday\"}}\n*{{nihongo|''Nichiy\u014dbi ni wa korosanai''|\u65e5\u66dc\u65e5\u306b\u306f\u6bba\u3055\u306a\u3044|extra=\"No Kills on Sunday\"}}\n*{{nihongo|''Ososugita ame no kay\u014dbi''|\u9045\u3059\u304e\u305f\u96e8\u306e\u706b\u66dc\u65e5|extra=\"The Belated Rain of Tuesday\"}}\n*{{nihongo|''Yami wa suiy\u014dbi ni otozureru''|\u95c7\u306f\u6c34\u66dc\u65e5\u306b\u8a2a\u308c\u308b|extra=\"Darkness Visits on Wednesday\"}}\n*{{nihongo|''Saraba d\u014dbi no kitakaze''|\u3055\u3089\u3070\u571f\u66dc\u65e5\u306e\u5317\u98a8|extra=\"Goodbye North-Wind of Saturday\"}}\n*{{nihongo|''Akujo mokuy\u014dbi ni shisu''|\u60aa\u5973\u6728\u66dc\u65e5\u306b\u6b7b\u3059|extra=\"Evil Woman dies on Thursday\"}}\n\n====The Hideo Yoake taxi-driver series====\n*{{nihongo|''Oikoshi kinshi: Doraib\u0101 tantei Yoake Hideo no jikenbo''|\u8ffd\u8d8a\u7981\u6b62\u2015\u30c9\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30fc\u63a2\u5075\u591c\u660e\u65e5\u51fa\u592b\u306e\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7c3f|extra=\"[[Overtaking|No Passing]]: Casebook of Driver Detective Hideo Yoake\"}}, Kodansha Novels<!--\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u30ce\u30d9\u30eb\u30ba)-->, 1991\n*{{nihongo|''Ipp\u014dts\u016bko: Doraib\u0101 tantei Yoake Hideo no jikenbo''|\u4e00\u65b9\u901a\u884c\u2015\u30c9\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30fc\u63a2\u5075\u591c\u660e\u65e5\u51fa\u592b\u306e\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7c3f|extra=\"One Way Street\"}}<!--(Kodansha Novels \u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u30ce\u30d9\u30eb\u30b9)-->, 1992\n*{{nihongo|''Hirusagari: Yoake Hideo no jikenbo''|\u663c\u4e0b\u304c\u308a\u2015\u591c\u660e\u65e5\u51fa\u592b\u306e\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7c3f|extra=\"Past Noon\"}}<!--(Kodansha Bunko \u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u6587\u5eab)-->, 1994\n*{{nihongo|''Yoake: Yoake Hideo no jikenbo''|\u591c\u660e\u3051\u2015\u591c\u660e\u65e5\u51fa\u592b\u306e\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7c3f|extra=\"Dawn\"}}, [[Nichibun]] Bunko<!--\u65e5\u6587\u6587\u5eab)-->, 1998\n*{{nihongo|''Y\u016bgure: Yoake Hideo no jikenbo''|\u5915\u66ae\u308c\u2015\u591c\u660e\u65e5\u51fa\u592b\u306e\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7c3f|extra=\"Evening\"}}<!--([[Nichibun]] Bunko \u65e5\u6587\u6587\u5eab)-->, 1999\n*{{nihongo|''Aribai no uta: Yoake Hideo no jikenbo''|\u30a2\u30ea\u30d0\u30a4\u306e\u5504\u2015\u591c\u660e\u65e5\u51fa\u592b\u306e\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7c3f|extra=\"Alibi Song:\"9}}<!--([[Nichibun]] \u65e5\u6587\u6587\u5eab)-->, 199\n*{{nihongo|''Seizon suru y\u016brei: Yoake Hideo no suiri nisshi''|\u751f\u5b58\u3059\u308b\u5e7d\u970a\u2015\u30bf\u30af